(1/2) Rambla ramble:

I first came to Siurana nearly 10 years ago after finishing high school. I was a completely different person and climber at the time — my focus was to have fun, explore, and be with my friends. The thought of trying 5.15 was laughable, at best.

At the time, I met @danieljungg who was working on La Rambla. He had told me that he was taking two rest days, this was a concept I was completely unfamiliar with 😂 Why would you take TWO rest days on a climbing trip?! Fast forward to this year and for the first time in my life I also took two rest days in a row 😅 Could be due to getting older or maybe getting wiser — we’ll never know.

It was only until relatively recently that I seriously considered the possibility that I could climb at this level. And still, even as I began this trip I was consumed with doing. More on that in the next post! 

Have any questions on my ascent or process?? Ask here and I will answer in the comments or into my next post 💖

1. Working burn
2. Pondering the moves and the draws 
3. Celebrating first major highpoint 
4. Sunrise to reflect after the send

La Rambla (2/2)
I arrived in Siurana feeling like I was in the best climbing form of my life. I spent weeks training at home to specifically increase my power and strength. I had a list of moonboard and kilterboard boulders that I wanted to send before leaving, and I ticked the final 4 in a last session with my friend @jwoojwoo. My strategy was to be strong enough to do all of the hardest moves relatively easily and gain the endurance while I was there - which is a natural strength of mine. I felt confident in my physical abilities but mentally I was intimidated. Was it too presumptuous to think that I could send 5.15?

My first day on the route went better than expected - I did all of the moves on my first try (with help from @marcozanone for the common beta). The process had begun. For the next few days I focused on linking longer sections and refining my beta. This part of the process was relatively comfortable - there was no pressure because I was just going bolt to bolt, could take if I was tired, and it was easy enough to get to the top of the route in this style.

Around this time I realized that I needed to change my approach. I could “work the moves” on this route forever but mentally I needed to switch into send mode. This was challenging because I was still struggling to make it through the crack crux at the bottom, which honestly felt embarrassing because of how low it is. I was battling my ego a lot on this route. Ultimately, I decided that I needed to prioritize every try. This led to my first real highpoint of making it through the crack twice in a day. 

Those of you who know me personally or have been following along for a while know that I am a serial stresser. It stems from intrinsic pressure I put on myself to meet my own expectations. I think that without it, I wouldn’t be as accomplished, but it is a brutal process with a lot of suffering. The stress started to sink in when I fell on the jump move about 1/3 of the way up 5 tries in a row. How could I ever hope to send this route if I’m not even linking up to the actual crux?

My body shut down after sending La Rambla.

It was the compilation of everything - physically and mentally. 

I was sore EVERY DAY that I bouldered in Switzerland. My body couldn’t recover no matter how much I ate, rested, or what grades I was trying. 

I felt conflicted while I was there because I knew I was fit enough to try some harder lines but emotionally I really didn’t feel like it and physically I was hurting. I decided to stick to the fun climbing, ease up on myself, and take a break when I got home. 

Today is going to be my first day climbing after a full week of rest. It was honestly so easy not to climb. I have my own stuff surrounding my climbing - expectations, goals, insecurities. I was worried it would be hard to take a week off and that I would feel guilty. I didn’t ¯\_(ツ)_/¯ and I’m not nervous to go back to it today either - I’m sure my arms will feel like gummy worms but honestly I love gummy worms so who cares.

In a couple days maybe I’ll get back on the boards and we can do some comparisons between now and while I was training for La Rambla. There are a lot of peaks and valleys that come with climbing performance (mine at least) and it will be fun to normalize the valleys a little bit.

I’ve been having intrusive thoughts/anxiety surrounding my body lately and a lot it felt like it stemmed from my climbing performance not meeting expectations.

Is it because of my body?

Yesterday I took a deep breath, put on a crop top, and went to a diff gym to change up the environment and hopefully have a reset.

I had the best @moonclimbing session of my life!! And guess what? IT IS BECAUSE OF MY BODY!

Just a Monday PSA to be kind to yourself. Sometimes I can easily get caught in the comparison trap of social media. My body doesn’t always look like the ones I see in my feed - but that’s ok! I have curves and my body fluctuates a lot. But she’s really strong 🥹

Joy.

I went into this trip with the objective of climbing boulders in my anti-style. I’ve been humbled both physically and mentally. It’s a lot of falling, a lot of failure. But I’m learning and I’m growing. And though the “grades” may not reflect it, I’m a much stronger and better climber than a year ago. That is something I’m so so proud of. 

I can’t remember a time where I’ve given up on a climb, it feels shameful but here I am. Sitting in a dark and damp cave I looked up at what felt like a million tick marks — they indicated sequences that I could maybe string together to make my way through this boulder. But I wasn’t happy to be there. I asked myself “why is this boulder even on my list?” The answer is simple: I haven’t done it. But is that a good enough reason? Not to me. What a difficult but important reminder to follow my joy, not my ego.

Here is a series of photos from my daily lap up Blue Sky of Mine — a boulder that makes me smile every time I climb it. An important part of my routine here in Magic Wood is starting the climbing day with a joyful moment — something which sharply juxtaposes the longer and arduous projecting sessions.

I went on a solo mish to After Hours V13/8B ⚡️yesterday
Managed to put it down in a couple of hours! This one suited me — heel hooks, 6mm crimps, fun toe hook to finish. Def on the softer side 🧸 (especially considering the FA @climbjoesvalley beta is a lot harder/bigger). But I’m psyched to see my fingers and biceps still WORK HARD after a month or two of sport climbing!! 😈

big goals usually come with big emotions — a lesson I relearned on Victimes del futur 5.14d/9a). 

I didn’t try this route until the last week of my trip, having spent the previous couple weeks intimidated by the Finestra cave in Margalef and consequently working up my confidence by trying other routes in the area. I quickly realized that I could send it but the clock was ticking. 

Ultimately, it came down to the last day of my trip, a type of pressure that makes me feel really UNCOMFORTABLE.

I fell twice in the crux. Then failed on a 3rd try even lower. I was STRESSED OUT. I felt irritable, disappointed, upset, and confused on what to do. It was easy to blame anything but me — weather, skin, vibe. The odds of sending on my 4th try on a steep, long, powerful route like this were low. My fingers were bleeding. I was unhappy and not having fun. 

I decided to leave the crag. I had a big snack and a small beer. 😉 I had to remove myself from the climb in order to figure out if I wanted to try again or accept that this was a project to return for. 

Of course, I tried again. And I did it, against all odds, even the ones I’d stacked against myself. Maybe because of that. 

Still working through the bigger lessons here. But there are a couple things that are certain:

1. I am still a serial stresser
2. I am learning to manage it
3. Cerveza for the send yet again 🍻

PSA I do not condone drinking and climbing lol I just needed to RELAX a tiny bit. Sometimes managing my stress means giving myself excuses. It’s hard to accept pure failure. But easier when I can blame it on a beer, or the fourth try, etc. When you can accept failure, it’s easier to succeed. ¯\_(ツ)_/¯
